DEFINITIONS (For Addenda Sections 10–15)

Work means the bio-fuel production processes, bio-battery designs, resonance-assisted catalysis protocols, and related technical implementations covered by this License.
Bio-Fuel means liquid or gaseous transportation fuel derived from biomass feedstock through biochemical or thermochemical conversion.
Bio-Battery means electrochemical energy storage systems utilizing biological materials or bio-derived compounds as active components, electrolytes, or structural elements.
Facility means any physical location where production operations occur.
Production means active manufacturing, processing, or synthesis of bio-fuel or bio-battery products at any scale. This term does not include laboratory research at <1 gallon total volume conducted under institutional safety protocols.

MANDATORY SAFETY AND ETHICAL ADDENDA
These sections override any conflicting permissive terms in Apache 2.0 where necessary to enforce safety and ethics. Violation of any addendum constitutes immediate and automatic termination of all rights under this License.
10. Mandatory Safety Standards
Production involves flammable liquids, chemical reactions, high temperatures/pressures, and risks of fire, explosion, or chemical exposure. ALL operations MUST comply with the following:
10.1 Facility and Operator Requirements
(a) Production SHALL NOT occur in residential dwellings, garages, sheds, basements, or non-commercial spaces.
(b) Facilities MUST be zoned for industrial/commercial use and comply with local fire, building, and environmental codes for hazardous materials.
(c) Minimum two (2) trained operators MUST be present during all active production runs. Solo operation is prohibited.
(d) Operators MUST have documented training in flammable liquid safety, emergency response, and relevant regulations.
10.2 Required Safety Infrastructure (minimum for all scales)

Commercial-grade fire suppression appropriate to fuel volume
Adequate ventilation for volatile organic compounds
Spill containment and grounding/bonding for transfer
Hazardous-location-rated electrical systems
Emergency shutdown procedures and equipment

10.3 Scale-Specific Requirements

Small-scale (<10,000 gallons/year equivalent): Annual safety inspection, $1M+ liability insurance
Medium-scale (10,000–1,000,000 gallons/year): Automatic suppression, quarterly audits, $5M+ insurance
Large-scale (>1,000,000 gallons/year): Full industrial standards, licensed engineers on staff, continuous monitoring, monthly third-party audits, $25M+ insurance

10.4 Laboratory Research Exception
Small-scale laboratory research (<1 gallon total volume, conducted by academic or non-profit institutions in appropriately equipped laboratory facilities under institutional safety protocols) is exempt from the professional facility and two-operator requirements. This exception does not apply to any commercial production at any scale.
10.5 Regulatory & Insurance Compliance

All required permits (fire, environmental, business) must be obtained and maintained
Adequate liability insurance must be in force at all times
Regular safety inspections by qualified authorities

WARNING
Bio-fuel and bio-battery production is inherently hazardous and involves risks of fire, explosion, chemical exposure, injury, or death.
IF YOU CANNOT FULLY COMPLY WITH SECTION 10 (professional facility, trained operators, permits, insurance, etc.), DO NOT USE THIS TECHNOLOGY.
The Licensor expressly disclaims all liability for non-compliant operations. No guidance, support, or license rights are provided for unsafe activities.
11. Environmental Integrity Mandate
The Work SHALL NOT be used to:
(a) Cause deliberate environmental degradation (unsustainable harvesting, water contamination/depletion, habitat destruction, biodiversity loss, toxic waste mishandling, GHG emissions beyond carbon-neutral lifecycle)
(b) Exploit resources or communities (unfair feedstock compensation, ecosystem destruction for profit, privatization of common resources)
(c) Support weaponization or coercive applications (military offensive fuels, energy systems for control/harm)
Violation terminates the License immediately.
12. Anti-Monopoly & Fair Dealing Covenant
(a) No enclosure of the commons: The knowledge and processes SHALL NOT be re-patented, locked behind restrictive terms, or used to create artificial scarcity or monopoly.
(b) Fair dealing: Feedstock providers SHALL receive fair market compensation; predatory pricing or market manipulation to eliminate competition is prohibited.
(c) No financial weaponization: Products SHALL NOT be used as instruments for pure speculation disconnected from physical production/delivery (standard hedging for legitimate business planning is permitted).
13. Safety-Critical Knowledge Sharing
(a) Any safety-related discovery (hazards, risks, failures, improvements) MUST be publicly disclosed within 30 days.
(b) Serious incidents (injuries, fires, environmental releases) MUST be reported to authorities immediately and to the Licensor within 7 days (public disclosure within 30 days unless restricted by investigation).
14. The Immutable Core
Sections 10–13 and this Section 14 form the Immutable Core and SHALL NOT be modified, waived, omitted, or contradicted in any derivative, sublicense, or redistribution.
Violation is a material breach, resulting in immediate termination of rights.
15. Scope, Enforcement, & Guidance
(a) Scope: Limited to bio-fuel and bio-battery technologies as defined.
(b) Enforcement: Licensor retains rights to terminate for violations, disclose breaches publicly, and pursue legal remedies.
(c) Legal note: Addenda may face enforceability challenges in some jurisdictions. They represent contractual and ethical commitments.
(d) Questions and Guidance: For questions regarding compliance with safety standards, environmental requirements, or ethical provisions, contact:
